<TEXT>
gov cecil andrus on tuesday signed into law 
a compromise bill making idaho the nations 47th state with an 
official holiday honoring civil rights leader martin luther king jr 
the law establishes martin luther king jridaho human rights 
day on the third monday in january corresponding with the federal 
holiday first observed in 1986 
idahos action leaves arizona montana and new hampshire the 
only holdouts not recognizing the federal holiday for king who was 
assassinated on april 4 1968 at the age of 39 
this historic legislation firmly demonstrates that idahoans 
have that broader concern for all humanity andrus said at a 
statehouse ceremony we stand against racism and for 
brotherhood 
kings widow coretta scott king issued a statement from 
atlanta commending andrus and the idaho legislature 
governor andrus has provided courageous leadeship in securing 
enactment of the holiday bill as well as some of the strongest 
antibias legislation in the nation mrs king said 
idahos 10th state holiday was approved by the legislature last 
month after lengthy sometimes bitter debate 
opponents focused on the cost of another paid day off for state 
employees which some put as high as 26 million and whether king 
should be singled out for the honor 
supporters cited the impact of kings nonviolent philosophy and 
his symbolic importance they also said the action was needed to 
help eliminate idahos stigma as a haven for racists such as the 
panhandlebased aryan nations critics dismissed that problem as 
exaggerated and the fault of irresponsible media coverage 
it took the addition of idaho human rights day to win over 
enough lawmakers for passage of the bill in the sessions closing 
hours 
idahos black population is estimated at 3200 or just over 
threetenths of 1 percent of the states approximately 1 million 
people 
new hampshire legislators have consistently voted down holiday 
proposals since 1979 after losing in 1989 supporters said they 
would try again in 1991 the next time legislative rules allow it 
lawmakers in montana with an even smaller black population than 
idaho made jan 15 a day of observance in 1987 and created 
heritage day a floating holiday to be designated by the governor 
the legislature in arizona the most populous state without an 
official king holiday approved a paid holiday for state employees 
last year but opponents petitioned to prevent the law from taking 
effect unless it is approved in a november referendum 
besides states without a king day north dakotas holiday is 
unpaid louisianas is by proclamation rather than legislation and 
is jan 19 marylands is on jan 15 whether or not that is a 
weekday and some states give employees other holiday options to 
substitute 
the legislative victory for idaho supporters of a king holiday 
was overshadowed somewhat by its timing while the bill was being 
adopted idaho also was embroiled in a national controversy over 
legislation that would have created the nations most restrictive 
antiabortion law 
andrus vetoed that measure only minutes after the legislature 
adjourned for the year march 30 then waited more than a week to 
make the king holiday bill law to ensure it would have center stage 
to itself 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

