<TEXT>
pledging there will be no turning back 
from parliamentary democracy king hussein is entrusting a 
committee with drafting guidelines for legalizing political parties 
outlawed 33 years ago 
hussein gathered the 60 members of the national charter 
committee on tuesday and pleaded on television for a pact that will 
guarantee tolerance for conflicting viewpoints 
the new phase with we are about to begin will pave the way for 
the resumption of political pluralism which is another cornerstone 
of democracy the 54yearold king said 
the constitutional parliamentary life is our common choice 
and the path from which there will be no turning back 
his speech had historic importance for this country of 31 
million people 
in november hussein oversaw jordans first national election 
since 1967 one of the freest ever held in the arab world 
he said the charter would form a broad and flexible framework 
for national action and would regulate the states various 
activities in politics economy security social affairs and 
culture 
he cautioned that without good will and agreement on basic 
concepts democracy turns into anarchy and develops fangs and 
talons that tear at the fabric of national unity and destroy the 
achievements and gains of the state 
hussein who has ruled since 1953 is relinquishing many powers 
but retains firm control and is personally popular 
the king said his july 1988 decision to renounce claims to the 
israelioccupied west bank in favor of the palestine liberation 
organization led to last novembers parliamentary election 
the west bank captured in the 1967 middle east war held half 
the seats in jordans old parliament it is not represented in the 
new body 
hussein said four days of widespread rioting over economic 
problems and government policies one year ago led him to seek the 
national charter 
he said the riots showed that elections alone would be an 
insufficient remedy because jordanians held varying convictions 
on some of the fundamental tenets and precepts upon which the 
kingdom is founded 
the king banned political parties in 1957 following an 
unsuccessful leftist coup attempt 
a nonparty parliament continued intermittently until 1974 
after a 10year hiatus it was revived in 1984 despite the lack of 
elections since 1967 
anyone who thinks that i was comfortable with the situation 
which prevailed in the absence of an elected parliament or that i 
was happy bearing most of the burden of government is 
mistaken said hussein 
he said the parties of the 1950s when panarab forces tried to 
spread their influence across national borders were governed by 
the positions and dictates of their leaders from abroad 
he accused them of seeking power at the expense of democracy 
and of violating another tenet of political pluralism which is 
to refrain from violence 
the king repeated that jordans commitment to help the 
palestinian people and their just cause is a historic and fateful 
part of its national commitment 
jordan will continue to exert all available resources to 
support the struggle of the palestinian people under its national 
leadership represented by the palestine liberation organization 
roughly half of jordans people come from palestinian families 
who fled or were driven from their homes by israels creation or 
its capture of the west bank 
</TEXT>
