police protection didnt prevent an attack on an 
underworlds office by a rival in a backhoe who destroyed a police 
car a guard house and a garage before 10 officers shot out the 
vehicles tires officials said 
it was the second time this year that a member of japans 
largest underworld organization the yamaguchigumi group used 
such a heavy construction vehicle against the office of the rival 
takenakagumi a local police official said 
two police officers and one mob member were injured in sundays 
attack in okayama 345 miles west of toyko 
police said the backhoe driven by toshiyuki okamoto 24 
dragged a patrol car 33 feet and smashed into the police guard 
house when officers tried to stop the attack 
okamoto damaged the office buildings gate and garage and 
several cars by repeatedly ramming into the building police said 
authorities often station police officers outside gang offices 
when violence is expected to protect the neighborhood and hopefully 
prevent confrontations 
one policeman was stabbed when he stopped one of several people 
who came out of the takenakagumi office and tried to attack 
okamoto who was protected by the backhoes bulletproof cab the 
official said 
okamoto and the man who stabbed the officer were both arrested 
the takenakagumi broke with the yamaguchigumi last year in 
protest over the appointment of yoshinori watanabe as the new gang 
boss 
watanabes predecessor masahisa takenaka was killed in a 
leadership dispute in 1985 the takenakagumi now is led by 
masahisa takenakas younger brother masashi 
police say the yamaguchigumi has about 21000 members 
nationwide the takenakagumi is widely believed to have been 
reduced to about 20 members 
police estimate japan has 90000 mob members nearly half 
associated with the three largest gangs the yamaguchigumi and 
the tokyobased inagawakai and sumiyoshi rengo 
members often wear badges identifying them as gang members 
although they do not admit to criminal activity 
police say the gangs are involved in extortion illicit 
gambling the drug and sex trades and money laundering some also 
have interests in the construction real estate and entertainment 
businesses 
