<TEXT>
telecommunications industry analysts say mcis 
merger with telecom usa inc will give the nations secondlargest 
longdistance company a chance for greater inroads into a market 
still dominated by american telephone amp telegraph co 
that could mean good news for consumers they say and even atampt 
is saying it hopes to benefit from the tougher competition 
mci communications corp and telecom usa the fourth largest 
company in the long distance market said monday that mci would 
acquire all outstanding shares of telecom usas stock for 42 a 
share for a total price of 125 billion 
the transaction is subject to approval by telecoms 
stockholders the federal communications commission also would have 
to grant approval and the justice department would review whether 
the deal would violate antitrust laws 
its a strategically important move bert c roberts jr 
mcis president and chief operating officer said in an interview 
it immediately brings us additional market share of about 1 
percent and against atampt as dominant a competitor as they are 
that efficiency is very important 
industry analysts agreed the acquisition should give mci a 
strong boost despite the cost because of telecoms active moves 
in advanced technology 
this shows the industry is consolidating at a very fast pace 
atampt is a very aggressive competitor and you have to move rapidly 
to grow this gives mci a further boost said charles nichols a 
telecommunications industry analyst for prudentialbache securities 
nichols and other analysts played down the stock market reaction 
to the mondays announcement which sent telecom usa soaring 1625 
to 3812 a share trading on the new york stock exchange mci 
dipped 112 to 3575 a share on the overthecounter market 
we think this puts mci and telecom in a favorable position 
said cathy clarke senior analyst for the yankee group a 
bostonbased consulting and marketing firm 
mci is growing and this will increase their potential to 
gain more of the market and provide more services she said 
the cost will have no effect on our ability to fund growth 
said roberts were in a very cashstrong position youre going 
to see that debt paid off very quickly within a couple of years 
mci revenues increased more than 20 percent in 1989 to 65 
billion while telecom had revenues of 713 million in sales last 
year atlantabased telecom was formed in 1988 with the merger of 
southernet of atlanta and teleconnect of cedar rapids iowa and 
serves customers primarily in the southeast and midwest 
atampt holds 64 percent of the long distance market down from 
about 90 percent before the courtordered breakup of the old bell 
system in 1984 mci has 12 percent and us sprint is third with 9 
percent according to the most recent fcc figures 
mci will gain the digital network and the fiber optic systems 
telecom has in place theyre going to gain a lot of network 
miles said the yankee groups clarke 
in this type of merger we expect to see cost savings 
improved quality of service improvements for customers such as 
onestop shopping so overall this should be good news for 
consumers she said 
even atampt said it was a good move the former monopoly is trying 
to convince the fcc that there is enough competition in the market 
to lift some regulations aimed solely at atampt 
this development suggests two vigorous companies are 
combining forces to provide even more competition said atampt 
spokesman herb linnen we wake up every day to a real knockdown 
dragout fight in the marketplace 
paul thibeau spokesman for no 3 sprint suggested there may be 
more mergers and acquisitions in the industry in the struggle to 
chip away at atampt the mci move should come as no surprise to 
those who follow the telecommunications industry he said we 
continue to explore similar opportunities 
mci will continue to focus on strategic acquisitions that make 
sense said roberts 
