cooperation in exchange markets 
however on monday the central banks of the group followed the 
statement with only weak and uncoordinated intervention traders 
said central banks intervene by buying yen in an attempt to push 
up its price 
also there was no indication that the united states and west 
germany were inclined to cut their interest rates to bolster the 
yen 
theyre basically leaving japan twisting in the wind said 
economist michael k evans a washingtonbased consultant there 
was just enough intervention so the japanese wouldnt have egg all 
over their face 
economists said although the group of sevens statement was 
slightly stronger in tone than expected it will not halt the yens 
slide unless japan does more to shore up its economy 
turmoil in the japanese stock market and political instability 
have helped push the yen down 11 percent in value compared with the 
dollar this year it hit a threeyear low of 160 yen to the dollar 
early last week before recovering somewhat before the meeting 
in tokyo the dollar fell 102 yen to 15645 yen monday but 
later in new york the dollar traded at 158335 yen up from 
fridays 15770 yen 
the market is just not really sure of the g7s resolve 
theyre going to have to come in collectively and so far they 
havent the intervention has seemed more of a gesture than a real 
movement said kevin lawrie a currency trader in new york with 
the bank of boston 
in order to stabilize its currency long term japan will have to 
further increase its interest rates said economist david wyss of 
drimcgraw hill a lexington mass forecasting firm 
an increase in japanese rates relative to us rates makes the 
yen a more attractive investment and raises its value the bank of 
japan raised its discount rate from 425 percent to 525 percent on 
march 20 but it was not enough to stem the yens slide 
since a march 23 meeting in los angeles between japanese finance 
minister ryutaro hashimoto and treasury secretary nicholas f 
brady japan had been asking for interest rate cuts in the united 
states and west germany 
but other countries are not inclined to help the japanese at the 
expense of their own economic objectives analysts said 
the west germans fear that lower rates will increase 
inflationary pressures in their country where the economy already 
is being stimulated by the prospect for investment in eastern 
europe and monetary union with east germany 
in the united states the federal reserve has been reluctant to 
cut rates until clearer evidence emerges that inflation is 
moderating 
for the fed to lower interest rates in the current inflation 
environment is not in the cards said economist allen sinai of 
the boston co 
in contrast with the fed the bush administration favors lower 
us interest rates both to stimulate economic growth and to help 
the us trade deficit economists said 
a weak yen pushes up the trade deficit by making japanese goods 
less expensive in the united states and raising the price of us 
goods in japan 
the group of seven officials will get a chance to reevaluate 
their stance at their next meeting in early may in washington 
</TEXT>
