<TEXT>
the ice is breaking on northern wisconsin 
lakes signaling the start of another tense spring when protesters 
head to boat landings to confront indians who use spears to catch 
spawning fish 
the first boats of chippewa indian spearfishers are expected to 
venture onto offreservation waters tonight to exercise a right 
guaranteed by 19th century federal treaties 
despite pleas for peace this springs spearfishing season is 
expected to renew confrontations between the chippewa and sport 
anglers who claim spearfishing is an unfair outdated practice 
that thins game fish populations 
observers are unsure whether tensions will escalate from a year 
ago when more than 200 protesters were arrested and the state and 
local sheriffs departments spent nearly 2 million to patrol the 
lakes 
nick hockings of the waswagon treaty association a group on 
the lac du flambeau chippewa reservation that organizes 
spearfishing outings thinks the crowds of antispearfishing 
protesters could be smaller weeded out to your racists 
as many as 1000 members of the american indian movement planned 
to travel from minnesota to northern wisconsin lakes to support the 
chippewa 
courts have ruled the chippewa are entitled to take up to 100 
percent of the safe harvest the number of fish that can be taken 
without harming future reproduction from each northern wisconsin 
lake 
but the chippewa have agreed to limit their catch this year to 
54 percent of the safe harvest or about 41410 walleyed pike on 
178 lakes the season usually lasts about three weeks in 1989 271 
spearfishers caught 16054 walleye 
