indians spearfished caused waves last year that made it difficult 
to see walleye preventing tens of thousands of fish from being 
caught he said 
the spearfishing dispute is rooted in treaties the chippewa 
signed when the tribe ceded millions of acres of northern wisconsin 
to the us government in the 1800s 
since 1983 federal courts have said the chippewa retained the 
right to hunt spearfish cut timber and gather foods on 
offreservation land in the ceded territory 
the rulings are being appealed but state officials including 
gov tommy g thompson said it could take nearly a decade for 
lawsuits to move through the courts 
unlike their ancestors who used torches modernday spearfishers 
wear hats with batteryoperated lights a walleye sluggish in the 
cold shallow water is stunned when it sees the light using iron 
spears the indians stab the fish from boats 
each spearfishing season has seen a gradual increase of tension 
and confrontations but state officials predicted 1990 might bring 
a downturn 
i think this will be a more peaceful season than in the 
past said george meyer chief of enforcement for the state 
department of natural resources while i dont believe tribal 
spearfishermen will be lonely on boat landings i believe there 
will be reduced tensions and levels of antitreaty rights 
demonstrations many people understand the issue cannot be 
resolved at boat landings 
