<TEXT>
albania 
thew last bastion of stalinist rule in what used to be communist 
eastern europe has rejected the democratic reforms that have swept 
the region the communist leadership which broke with moscow in 
the 1960s has made clear it has no intention of relinquishing its 
leading role or staging free elections 
chairman nominal head of state ramiz alia communist 
premier adil carcani communist 
cabinet includes 24 members all believed to be communists 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
bulgaria 
the balkan country of 9 million plans to hold its first 
multiparty elections since world war ii on june 10 and june 17 
under terms worked out between the ruling communists renamed the 
socialists this month and opposition parties and groups 
president petar mladenov unaffiliated officially no longer 
with the socialist party 
premier andrei lukanov now socialist 
parliament has some 400 members 75 percent of whom are former 
communists turned socialists parliament is in a state of 
dissolution pending the june elections 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
czechoslovakia 
multiparty elections are scheduled for june 89 for the 
