alcoholic beverages and four out of 10 would support a ban on 
advertisements that promote alcohol a nationwide poll shows 
the gallup poll released monday was commissioned by 
advertising age magazine and conducted april 5 two days after 
federal legislation was introduced proposing that health warnings 
be displayed on all alcoholic beverages and ads 
seventythree percent of those surveyed support health warnings 
only 13 percent said they oppose the warnings 
fortytwo percent of those polled also favor an outright ban on 
alcoholic beverage advertising only 49 percent said they were 
opposed to banning all beer wine and liquor advertising the rest 
were unsure 
six out of 10 said they believed putting warning labels on 
alcohol would have some effect on americas consumption of wine 
liquor and beer thirtysix percent said it would have no effect 
thirtyeight percent of those questioned said they drink alcohol 
either frequently or occasionally but sixtytwo percent said they 
rarely or never drink 
support for the warnings is highest among those who said they 
rarely drink 79 percent or never drink 76 percent and lower 
among those who said they drink frequently 64 percent 
the legislation introduced would require every print and 
broadcast ad to carry one of five messages about alcohols effects 
including its association with birth defects when consumed by 
pregnant women 
gallup questioned a random sample of 823 adults by telephone 
the poll has a margin of error of plus or minus 35 percent 
