dismissed the suit 
c peter erlinder bellecourts attorney said he plans to ask 
the us supreme court to review the case or request that the 
entire court in the 8th circuit rehear it 
the appeals panel ruled that bellecourt had given up his right 
to privacy when he dropped his film off at a shop in minneapolis 
that had a processing machine located next to a glass wall the 
transparent wall allowed anyone to observe the photos briefly as 
they were being printed at the fstop one hour photo store 
a clerk at the store agreed to sell a duplicate set of pictures 
to an fbi agent who had been trailing bellecourt the clerk later 
told the indian leader about the duplicate photos and bellecourt 
sued the fbi 
the appeals panel ruled that bellecourts use of the fstop for 
photo processing exposed his photographs to the public sufficiently 
to defeat his claim to fourth amendment privacy protection 
with this ruling it appears there are a lot of places that 
people go to in their everyday lives that now are potential 
government information pickup points erlinder said 
