<TEXT>
growing congestion could bring air travel in 
western europe to a near standstill within the next 10 years 
unless air space management is radically reorganized a report 
released today warned 
the congestion has already caused serious problems said the 
report which was prepared for the international air transport 
association or iata one out of every four flights was delayed by 
more than 15 minutes last year costing the industry about 5 
billion for additional fuel and other expenses it said 
with european air traffic expected to double to 500 million 
passengers by the year 2000 and to triple by 2010 present capacity 
of the transport system will be unable to cope with increases in 
air travel past 1995 it said 
the report which has been sent to all governments concerned is 
based on a oneyear study conducted by iata and compiled by sri 
international the us based consulting firm 
of the three major airport areas london frankfurt and 
paris only paris has excess capacity it said no solution is 
seen for frankfurts capacity shortfall passenger growth at the 
three london area airports will exceed terminal capacity by the 
mid1990s and aircraft movement will exceed runway capacity by 
the year 2004 
without enhancement 16 west european airports will be unable 
to accommodate air traffic demand in the year 2000 according to a 
summary of runway capacities included in the report 
in the order of seriousness those airports include madrid 
frankfurt londongatwick londonheathrow barcelona 
milanlinate duesseldorf dublin stockholm athens palma de 
mallorca geneva manchester marseille copenhagen and hamburg 
the report said by implementing potential improvements most 
airports could meet the demand forecast but it stressed that this 
would require overcoming political environmental and financial 
obstacles 
iata director general guenter eser who presented the report 
agreed at a news conference that fighting environmental concerns 
will be an uphill battle commenting on the airspace situation the 
report said one of the most serious problems is the increasing 
complexity of an air traffic control system that has to cope with a 
steadily increasing number of aircraft 
it also pointed to the fast growing numer of airway 
intersections and called for the creation of new routes to minimize 
such crossing traffic 
the necessary drastic restructuring should include sectors 
reserved up top now for military use the report stressed 
a radical reorganization of the way in which west european 
airspace is urgent and essential if the regions air transport 
system is not to be brought to a near standstill in the late 1990s 
because of congestion it summed up 
it called for an early international conference of all 
governments airlines and international aviation organizations 
including iata which groups 190 airlines including all of the 
worlds major carriers 
such a conference the report said should discuss ways and 
means of tackling the problem before it is too late 
