<TEXT>
nelson mandela will lead an 
11member african national congress delegation in groundbreaking 
talks next month with the government on ending whiteminority rule 
the organization said tuesday 
following the may 24 talks mandela will embark on a series of 
foreign trips to at least nine countries including the united 
states the soviet union and several african and european nations 
the anc said 
next months discussions are designed to clear the way for 
formal negotiations on a new constitution that will give the 
28million black majority a share of power in the country 
it is vital that this meeting achieve the necessary results in 
terms of removing the obstacles that continue to stand in the way 
of negotiations the anc said in a statement from its exile 
headquarters in lusaka zambia 
the anc has said those obstacles include lifting the state of 
emergency allowing exiles to return to south africa and releasing 
antiapartheid activists convicted of politically motivated crimes 
the government which had previously announced the dates for the 
talks has made clear that several black opposition groups in 
addition to the anc will be invited to take part in the formal 
negotiations on a new constitution 
the anc founded in 1912 has never held formal negotiations 
with the whiteminority government although mandela has met with 
president fw de klerk and his predecessor pw botha 
the talks originally were set for april 11 but the anc called 
off that meeting to protest a march 26 police shooting that left at 
least 11 protesters dead in sebokeng a township south of 
johannesburg 
the anc delegation will include leaders from inside the country 
such as walter sisulu and ahmed kathrada they were released last 
year after more than 26 years in prison 
exile leaders named to take part in the talks include anc 
secretarygeneral alfred nzo the commander of the ancs military 
wing joe modise and the director of international affairs thabo 
mbeki 
the anc did not release the exact dates of mandelas trips 
however they will begin after the discussions with the government 
and last until early july 
in addition to the united states and the soviet union mandela 
is scheduled to visit france west germany canada egypt angola 
nigeria and algeria 
de klerk released mandela in february after the black 
nationalist leader spent 27 years in prison for sabotage and 
plotting to overthrow the government mandela was named deputy 
president of the anc after his release 
also in february de klerk legalized the anc and more than 60 
other black opposition groups as part of his effort to launch 
negotiations 
the anc and other antiapartheid groups want a oneperson 
onevote democracy de klerk has opposed this saying it will 
replace white domination with black domination 
de klerk envisions a mechanism that would allow whites to 
maintain veto power on major policy decisions 
