the soviet union made a strong pitch 
tuesday for western help in making freemarket reforms by asking 
for talks to ease restrictions on the sale of high technology 
stepan sitarian a deputy soviet premier said such western 
limits should no longer remain a sacred cow 
the premier also hailed a new international accord reached 
monday in bonn that committed the soviets to backing freemarket 
economic reform he said the pact conformed to president mikhail s 
gorbachevs reform program known as perestroika 
many of the decisions and recommendations contained in the 
bonn document are in line with our philosophy of perestroika and 
have a direct bearing on the economic renewal in the soviet 
union sitarian said in a speech to the 35nation conference on 
economic cooperation in europe the conference ends wednesday 
sitarian also made it clear the soviets hope for western help in 
carrying out economic change he said success in implementing the 
bonn accord will depend on countries meeting each other half 
way 
sitarian said the wests socalled cocom restrictions on 
hightechnology sales to the east bloc present certain 
complications to restructuring the soviet economy 
cocom stands for the 17nation coordinating committee for 
multilateral export controls the western cocom restrictions were 
adopted during the cold war to prevent the soviet bloc from gaining 
sensitive technology 
we believe that few businessmen would be willing to cooperate 
in an outdated technical basis sitarian told reporters after his 
speech 
we propose that eastwest consultations begin on rules to 
govern the transfer of dualpurpose technology he said 
referring to products and equipment that can be used for civilian 
or military purposes 
he said the soviet union is willing to agree to inspection 
procedures so the west can verify that hightechnology equipment is 
not being used for military purposes 
the cocom nations are already working on proposals for loosening 
restrictions on technology sales to reforming east bloc countries 
however the united states has indicated it will take a tougher 
stand toward the soviet union 
sitarian said the soviet union is committed to carrying out 
price reforms as soon as possible he said it is also eager to make 
its currency the ruble convertible 
in mondays pact the 35 nations at the conference the united 
states canada and all european countries except albania 
informally endorsed a document committing them to support private 
property free enterprise and multiparty democracy 
such a move would have been unthinkable months ago before the 
wave of democratic and economic reform in the east bloc 
