<TEXT>
us participation in an international 
development bank for the soviet union and eastern europe is now 
assured because of limits put on soviet borrowing the treasury 
said tuesday 
the agreement among 42 countries involved was announced monday 
in paris where officials said an accord creating the european bank 
for reconstruction and development will be signed may 30 
for three years the soviet union will be allowed to borrow only 
as much as it pays in or about 216 million treasury spokesman 
robert levine said 
the soviets will contribute 6 percent of the banks 12 billion 
capital but participating countries will pay in less than a third 
of their capital share with the rest on call the united states 
will have the largest share 10 percent the member countries of 
the european economic community will have 51 percent among them 
similar intergovernment banks like the world bank have larger 
proportions of their capital on call but never actually call it 
because they get most of their money for loans by borrowing 
themselves on financial markets 
jacques attali an adviser to french president francois 
mitterrand said monday in paris that a twoday meeting agreed on 
58 articles of the banks statutes settling such outstanding 
issues as the type of currency to be used in the bank and the 
amount and form of capital contributions of each member 
the delegates agreed that the us dollar japanese yen and 
european currency unit all can be used to contribute capital to the 
bank the ecu is worth about 120 
a president for the bank still has to be chosen and several 
european cities are competing to have the headquarters officials 
hope it can start making loans by the end of this year 
at the first session to set terms for the bank in january the 
united states objected to full participation by the soviet union 
unless moscow initiated major market reforms 
in addition to the united states and virtually every european 
country participants in the bank include japan morocco israel 
egypt and south korea 
levine said the banks charter will also require borrowers to be 
moving toward democracy a requirement the united states wanted and 
the soviets opposed 
he added that an additional curb on loans to the soviets will be 
a requirement that their borrowings be either for private 
enterprises or for enterprises operating competitively and moving 
toward a market orientation that could include some stateowned 
enterprises 
for all borrowers 60 percent of the loans must go to the 
private sector levine said the other 40 percent can be used for 
government infrastructure projects roads bridges water supply 
transport or to improve the environment 
the limit on loans to the soviets can be changed in three years 
but only by an 85 percent vote of the participating countries 
</TEXT>
