<TEXT>
participants in an international media conference 
said tuesday that soviet leader mikhail s gorbachevs reforms and 
new communications technology have combined to open up the east 
bloc to the rest of the world 
but at least one western journalist taking part in the 11th 
world media conference expressed concern over the closing of 
lithuania and other restive soviet republics to foreign reporters 
the world media conference meeting for the first time in 
moscow began a threeday symposium tuesday to discuss the impact 
of political changes in the soviet union on international 
communications 
about 500 delegates from 60 countries including many former 
heads of state attended the meeting of the association which was 
founded by the rev sun myung moon to encourage eastwest 
communications 
allen h neuharth founder of the newspaper usa today told an 
afternoon panel discussion that advanced satellite communications 
and publishing technology have opened a new window on the world 
he said people around the world were able to watch the events 
unfolding in the soviet union and eastern europe on television and 
read about them almost immediately in newspapers 
there are no more secrets in the world neuharth said 
he said the media now and in the future would play a key role 
in the shaping of global events it is the glue that will hold 
the globe together or tear it apart he said 
andrei grachev deputy director of the communist party central 
committees international affairs department agreed 
the 20th century began as an age of electronics and is ending 
as the age of communications grachev said 
we are living in an age where secrets cannot be kept he 
said citing the example of foreign scientists who detected the 
1986 chernobyl nuclear disaster and satellite intelligence on the 
location of nuclear missile sites 
