<TEXT>
the soviet military is playing its most 
visible role in kremlin politics in three years us government 
analysts said tuesday 
the sources cite last weeks setback in superpower armscontrol 
talks and moscows hardline response to the lithuanian 
independence movement 
the two developments appear to be related said one 
administration source who like others spoke on the condition he 
not be further identified 
while offering several possible explanations for why military 
officers are playing a more prominent role than at any time since 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev reshuffled the military 
command in june 1987 analysts said they did not think that the 
military had increased its power at gorbachevs expense 
but military officers do seem to be flexing their muscles a 
little more said one source noting that soviet officers have 
played a key role in the response to lithuanias attempts to become 
an independent nation 
analysts offered these scenarios 
one possibility is that the military is increasing its 
prominence on instructions from gorbachev 
there is no doubt in my mind that although the military is 
playing a more visible role the decisions are being made by 
political authorities said one administration armscontrol 
expert 
a second theory is that gorbachev is allowing the military to 
play a heavyhanded role in lithuania if the approach fails he 
can simply walk away from it and say that it was not his policy 
after all said another source 
a third possibility is that gorbachev and other civilian 
leaders are preoccupied and that military officers are filling the 
vacuum where they see their interests threatened one analyst said 
the more visible military role became clear shortly after 
lithuania declared independence on march 11 
the commander of all soviet ground forces gen valentin i 
varennikov was present in lithuania as soviet forces seized 
government party and publishing offices arresting deserters from 
the soviet army and rumbling through vilnius in tanks 
as for arms control a setback became apparent last week during 
talks in washington between secretary of state james a baker iii 
and soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze 
us negotiators were working on the assumption that we would 
make progress at the same rate we have since last year what we had 
to hoped to accomplish at the meeting did not get done said one 
administration source 
over the last year the soviets made concessions on three major 
start issues their objection to the strategic defense initiative 
their insistence that the treaty cover submarinelaunched cruise 
missiles slcms and rules for counting airlaunched cruise 
missiles alcms 
last week the soviets revived their demand that the treaty 
require the two sides to issue a separate declaration setting 
limits on slcms administration sources said 
the soviets also revived their insistence that the treaty cover 
all alcms with ranges above 360 miles the americans want to count 
only missiles above 900 miles thus excluding alcms aboard tactical 
warplanes such as the f15 and the f111b the sources said 
one source interpreted the tougher soviet arms position as a 
retrenchment by the soviet military 
they were apparently angry over the concessions made by 
civilian negotiators and wanted to regain some lost ground one 
administration source said 
however another source attributed the change to kremlin tactics 
designed to increase pressure on the americans as negotiators 
struggle to complete a start deal before the summit 
president bush meeting with reporters as he flew to toronto to 
attend a baseball game and meet with canadian prime minister brian 
mulroney commented on both developments 
on lithuania he said he had warned the kremlin that a crackdown 
could damage superpower relations 
ive made our position very clear peaceful resolution of 
this question because we do not recognize that the use of force 
would accomplish anything other than to set back relations and i 
think they know that loud and clear by now very clear bush said 
on the slowdown on armscontrol progress bush said he still 
hopes the two sides can complete a proposed strategic arms 
reduction treaty to cut longrange nuclear arsenals by 30 to 50 
percent 
