<TEXT>
half of america has already stood up to be 
counted 
the census bureau reported tuesday that the response rate for 
its 1990 national head count has reached 50 percent 
we expect the number to grow said spokeswoman paulette 
lichtmanpanzer noting that the halfway mark was reached last 
friday 
and that response rate counted only forms that have been 
logged in by census offices across the nation she said many 
places have a backlog of returns waiting to be checked in 
the bureau mailed out 88 million forms on march 23 and hand 
delivered an additional 11 million to homes where proper mailing 
addresses could not be obtained 
in addition census takers are working with postal officials to 
correct problems in several communities where forms could not be 
delivered for one reason or another officials said 
if anyone has put off answering the census nows the time to 
do so said lichtmanpanzer stressing the need to increase the 
mail response rate 
census officials have told congress that they hope for a 70 
percent response rate sending workers out to count those who do 
not answer the mailed request costs an estimated 10 million for 
every percentage point officials have estimated 
census offices will begin sending out workers april 26 to homes 
where no form has been sent back said lichtmanpanzer 
they will try to interview the residents to get the necessary 
information in some cases she pointed out homes are vacant or 
may have been torn down resulting in no form being returned 
while half the census forms are now back tabulating the 
information they contain will take months 
the first results of the census population totals for each 
state will be reported on dec 31 and more detailed information 
will follow after the first of the year 
the total cost of the census is expected to reach 25 billion 
the national head count is conducted every 10 years it is 
required by the constitution to produce population totals used in 
reapportioning seats in the house of representatives in addition 
census population totals are used in dividing up billions of 
dollars in federal funds for state and local governments 
