<TEXT>
a houston firm agreed to divest its diamond 
drill bit business to avoid a justice department antitrust suit 
over its proposed 550 million purchase of a salt lake city 
company according to court papers filed tuesday 
the justice department simultaneously filed the antitrust suit 
challenging the proposed acquisition of eastman christensen co of 
salt lake city by baker hughes inc of houston along with a 
consent decree settling the suit 
diamond drill bits are used to drill for oil and gas and both 
companies are large diversified suppliers of a wide variety of oil 
field products and services 
the two companies are major manufacturers of three types of 
diamond drill bits natural diamond bits synthetic diamond bits 
called polycrystalline diamond compact bits and thermally stable 
synthetic polycrystalline diamond bits 
in the united states last year sales of the three types of 
diamond drill bits totaled more than 30 million baker hughes 
accounted for about 15 percent or 46 million and eastman 
christensen accounted for about 25 percent or 77 million 
according to the justice department 
worldwide baker hughes earned about 18 million of its total 
sales of 23 billion from its diamond drill bit business the 
department said for eastman christensen worldwide diamond drill 
bit sales accounted for 35 million of its 211 million total sales 
the antitrust suit filed in us district court in the district 
of columbia alleged that the proposed acquisition would hamper 
competitiveness in the us market for those three types of drill 
bits 
the divestiture will ensure that the merger of baker hughes 
and eastman christensen will not raise the cost of drilling for oil 
and gas in the united states james f rill assistant attorney 
general in charge of the antitrust division said in a statement 
under the consent decree baker hughes must divest its entire 
diamond drill bit business including foreign and domestic 
facilities by aug 6 or a trustee will be appointed to carry out 
the divestiture the department said 
baker hughes diamond drill bit business includes its patents 
manufacturing facilities in houston aberdeen scotland and 
escobar argentina and a research and development center 
</TEXT>
