president mikhail s gorbachev said tuesday he and 
senior government advisers will agree before the end of the week on 
a muchanticipated program of radical economic reform 
he said he wants to quicken the pace for overhauling the economy 
his announcement came as senior soviet officials debate whether 
to initiate polishstyle economic shock therapy here that would 
free prices and sharply increase unemployment while slashing the 
value of the ruble 
the officials have cautioned however that the government will 
be able to go only as fast as angry and disillusioned consumers 
allow 
on tuesday gorbachev told a congress of the komsomol communist 
youth group analyzing the situation we came to the conclusion 
that it is necessary to speed up economic reform already this year 
and at the beginning of next year we will take the basic steps in 
this direction that were planned for 19921993 
gorbachev said the presidential council and the council of the 
federation two new advisory groups formed after he took office 
last month as the countrys first executive president will meet 
saturday to decide on proposals from government ministers to put 
reforms into effect 
soviet leaders want to boost industrial production and remedy 
perennial shortages of a range of consumer goods 
gorbachev said the proposals will be presented for public debate 
before they go into effect he did not go into particulars 
one day earlier deputy premier leonid abalkin dodged questions 
on the details of economic reform at a news conference creating 
the impression the government still had not decided many questions 
abalkin also said public worries about rising prices and 
unemployment were a key factor 
a speedy transition to a market economy will come up against 
powerful opposition he said 
what we must do first is to make all people understand and see 
clearly that without such a transition the country has no future as 
a highly developed great power abalkin said 
