<TEXT>
manuel pereira stared at the floor and 
explained how his dream of owning a home was destroyed or at least 
postponed by new government rules that wont let him spend his own 
money 
for 27 years pereira tucked something away in a savings account 
each week so he could buy a home before retiring from his job as a 
doorman 
last month at 63 he had enough for the down payment on a 
twobedroom apartment 
something else happened last month fernando collor de mello 
became president of brazil on march 15 and took drastic action to 
stop annual inflation of 4850 percent 
banks closed for five days new taxes were imposed utility 
rates increased by 30 percent to 80 percent up to 80 percent of 
the value of a savings or money market account was frozen for 18 
months 
all of a sudden everything i worked for was gone pereira 
said how can i believe in anything anymore 
brazilians are unable to get at their money and fear it will be 
worth less when and if it is returned private companies lay off 
workers in droves 
confidence is waning and optimism is turning to despair in a 
vast nation of 150 million people that is potentially among the 
worlds richest but polls show most brazilians still are willing 
to give collors ideas a chance 
miriam santos de lima partowner of a restaurant has lost her 
trust the government lied to us she said collor promised 
he wouldnt touch our savings and he swept them into the government 
safe this is a disasterous start for a government pretending to be 
honest and clean 
confidence in banks is at an alltime low people are turning to 
the black market stashing us dollars in cabinets and under their 
mattresses 
even under collors strict rules anyone with a savings account 
can withdraw the equivalent of 1200 for money market accounts 
and certificates of deposit the limit is 600 or 20 percent 
whichever is greater 
nearly everyone seems to be using the opportunity 
im taking all my money out of the bank because if they took 
the money of the biggies ours will be next housewife rosa marie 
da silva said withdrawing the 100 in her account at the banerj 
bank in the hilltop rocinha slum 
a formerly hyperactive economy seems moribund 
consumers and manufacturers who furiously speculated bought and 
sold when inflation roared along at 200 percent a week now wait in 
lines at banks to withdraw what they can to pay for overhead or 
living expenses 
investments debts weddings honeymoons all are on hold 
bartering is commonplace 
