heres a list to keep handy in the kitchen of what to buy what 
not to buy what to do and what not do to help protect the 
environment the list is compiled from guidelines published by 
several environmental groups 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
products that are recycled recyclable reliable repairable 
refillable reusable and longlasting 
bulk products in large containers to cut down packaging 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
fresh fruits and vegetables rather than canned or frozen 
varieties 
organic food locally grown if possible 
soft drinks or beer in return bottles cans are a second choice 
but avoid plastic rings on sixpacks 
juices in concentrate form 
eggs in fiberboard cartons instead of plastic foam cartons 
loose leaf tea rather than tea bags 
milk in bottles instead of cartons 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
highefficiency electrical appliances if possible buy 
handoperated tools or appliances rather than electric or motorized 
ones 
microwave ovens pressure cookers and other energysaving 
devices 
compact fluorescent light bulbs or other lowwatt longlasting 
bulbs 
paper trash bags instead of plastic bags 
canvas or mesh bags to carry groceries instead of paper or 
plastic bags 
cloth napkins and towels 
cloth diapers instead of disposable diapers 
phosphatefree biodegradable soaps and detergents 
longlasting razor blades 
tube toothpaste rather than hard plastic pumps 
lipstick brush to use all the lipstick in a tube 
permanent or reusable coffee filters 
reusable refrigerator and freezer containers 
reusable plastic dishes cups and utensils for picnics 
recycled paper products such as toilet paper greeting cards 
stationery childrens playbooks and drawing sheets 
tampons with cardboard applicators or no applicators 
biodegradable cat litter 
rechargeable batteries 
faucet aerators for each sink 
lowflow shower heads 
radial tires 
fuelefficient vehicles 
natural pest control products instead of toxic pesticides 
thermostats for heaters 
timer for outdoor lights 
weather stripping insulation and caulking for windows and doors 
solar energy panels where possible 
woodburning stoves and fireplace inserts 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
overpackaged products 
plastic wrap 
aluminum foil 
throwaway items such as plastic razors 
aerosols styrofoam and other products with chlorofluorocarbons 
cfcs 
foods out of season 
tv dinners with plastic or aluminum trays 
soup in plastic containers 
