prices in some key product lines disappointments in manufacturing 
operations and a higher effective tax rate led to a 193 percent 
decline in its firstquarter profit 
the purchase nybased paper and forest products maker said it 
earned 180 million or 165 a share in the three months ended 
march 31 down from 223 million or 196 a share a year earlier 
revenue rose 231 percent to 32 billion from 26 billion 
john a georges chairman and chief executive said the results 
were affected by lower prices in paper pulps and printed and 
writing papers 
the deepest price cuts came in uncoated printing and writing 
papers he said recent increases in industry capacity led to 
price reductions even though sales volume remained at healthy 
levels he said 
he said paper pulp price declines stemmed from inventory 
corrections by customers 
manufacturing costs rose at some mills due to higher wood prices 
and weatherrelated conditions georges said production 
interruptions associated with capital projects and process 
modifications also affected the performance of the mill systems he 
said 
these situations were temporary and manufacturing conditions 
are returning to normal he said 
the companys effective tax rate for the quarter rose to 40 
percent from 38 percent a year ago he said 
georges said the companys other businesses posted improved 
performances citing contributions to operating income from recent 
acquisitions speciality products businesses and consumer packaging 
while the uncertainty of future economic conditions makes it 
difficult to predict performance we believe that our investments 
in new markets development of additional higher value products and 
improved operating efficiencies should provide the basis for 
continuing good financial results he said 
