<TEXT>
federal safety officials today concluded that 
failures by the airline the manufacturer and the government all 
contributed to the loss of a cargo door on united flight 811 over 
the pacific ocean last year nine passengers were blown out of the 
aircraft to their deaths 
the national transportation safety board voted 30 to blame 
united airlines boeing and the federal aviation administration in 
the feb 24 1989 accident which has already led to faa action to 
ensure that boeing 747 cargo doors are secure 
the board said united failed to properly inspect the door of the 
airliner after its electrical system failed in december 1988 and 
mechanics had to operate it manually it had been operating 
electrically since then however 
boeing and the faa were cited for failing to order timely 
corrective measures after another cargo door malfunctioned on a 
1987 pan american flight from london to new york the board noted 
however that the faa has since issued directives for improving the 
doors and plans additional action 
united spokesman robert dowdy said the airline has complied with 
all faa requirements except one that resulted from a clerical 
error six words mandating an inspection were left out of a 
regulation when it was copied from faa documents into the company 
system investigators said 
dowdy said the board conducted a good investigation with the 
evidence it had but said recovery of the cargo door itself is 
needed to make it morethorough boeing had recommended that the 
board conclude that probable cause of the incident could not be 
determined 
in seattle boeing spokesman jack gamble said the company had no 
comment on the ntsb finding except to say we feel no 1 those 
cargo doors are safe 
there were subsequent changes made as a result of the 
accident changes and inspection processes all of the necessary 
actions have been taken to ensure integrity of that doors 
operation in flight gamble said 
the faa is expected to issue a new order requiring an additional 
warning system in boeing747 cargo doors to indicate to the pilot 
and the ground crew that the doors are properly locked 
investigators told the board 
the board said there is evidence that the current system can 
indicate that the door is locked when it is not 
the plane returned to honolulu from a scheduled flight to new 
zealand after the door popped off at about 22000 feet ripping off 
a 15by10foot section of the fuselage and hurling a group of 
passengers and their seats out of the aircraft 
five other passengers were seriously hurt and 33 received minor 
injuries the plane carried a crew of 18 and 337 passengers 
ron schleed investigator in charge for the accident said 
efforts to locate and recover the cargo door from three miles below 
the ocean would continue despite the fact the board has completed 
its report he said a navy vessel and sophisticated probe device 
would be available in june to search for the door 
investigators hope to determine exactly what failure in the 
mechanism may have caused the door to fly off although they 
believe it was caused by damage to devices either during manual 
opening and closing of the door or due to a electrical malfunction 
</TEXT>
