<TEXT>
ual corp said tuesday it had formalized its 
agreement to sell the company the parent of united airlines to 
its employees for about 438 billion 
the definitive merger agreement follows the signing friday of an 
agreement in principle between chicagobased ual and its employee 
unions representing uniteds pilots machinists and flight 
attendants 
the formalization of the buyout pact sets into motion the 
process for leaders of the three unions to seek rankandfile 
approval of wage cuts and other contract concessions designed to 
save 2 billion over five years as a contribution toward the buyout 
the wage cuts range from 5 percent for flight attendants with 
less than five years of seniority to 11 percent for pilots with 
more than five years 
under the agreement uals 71000 employees will buy 100 percent 
of the company by exchanging for each share of ual stock 155 in 
cash 35 in ual notes and one share in covia corp valued at 11 
covia is a computerized reservations company in which ual holds 
a 50 percent interest 
the deal valued at 201 a share could take up to eight months 
to complete the agreement gives the employees four months to 
secure financing and another four months to complete the deal 
hank krakowski a spokesman for the union group said he 
envisioned ratification of the contracts within a month or two at 
the extreme 
leaders of the united chapter of the air line pilots association 
planned to hold an informational meeting wednesday for chicagoarea 
pilots then take the show on the road to united pilots in other 
cities according to a recorded message on the unions information 
hotline 
