<DOCNO> AP900410-0238 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a court ruling that insurance 
companies are liable for up to 960 million in damages for asbestos 
exposure could clear the way for settlement of thousands of claims 
a victims advocate said tuesday 
the five insurance companies reacted with caution to the ruling 
by a new jersey superior court judge which involved claims 
stemming from asbestos products made by owensillinois corp from 
1948 to 1958 
heather maurer executive director of the asbestos victims of 
america in soquel calif which represents more than 8000 people 
the decision is a key step to resolving lawsuits filed against 
asbestos manufacturers 
this basically means that our asbestos victims now have 
recourse and the manufacturers no longer will be able to say we 
dont have any money to pay you because our insurance companies 
wont pay us she said 
andrew berry an attorney for owensillinois of toledo ohio 
said the ruling last friday was the largest of its kind involving 
claims against an asbestos manufacturer 
owensillinois had sought a ruling to determine whether its five 
insurance companies would be liable to cover damage awards the 
insurers claimed that asbestosrelated lawsuits were excluded from 
policies written between 1977 and 1985 
asbestos is widely used in building materials and as a 
soundproofing and fireproofing agent it has been linked to 
health problems and deaths caused by tiny particles that become 
trapped in the lungs 
allstate insurance co one of the five companies involved in 
the decision said in a statement tuesday it was surprised and 
disappointed with the ruling 
allstate based in northbrook ill said its exposure to claims 
would not exceed 25 million and thus would not threaten the health 
of the company 
general reinsurance co a stamford connbased firm that 
assumed much of the insurance exposure of owens insurance ltd an 
owenillinois subsidiary said the asbestos claims would not impact 
its earnings or financial condition 
both companies said the decision would be reviewed to whether to 
appeal 
owensillinois claimed in the 5yearold lawsuit insurers 
wrongfully refused to honor claims the judge rejected insurers 
arguments that the owensillinois policies did not cover asbestos 
damage berry said 
most of the 75000 suits against owensillinois involved 
individuals and companies claiming injuries and damages stemming 
from the use of an insulation product manufactured by 
owensillinois he said 
included were claims of asbestosis and other forms of lung 
cancer linked to asbestos exposure 
asbestos exposure also has been linked to cancers of the 
esophagus and colon and to mesothelioma an alwaysfatal cancer of 
the lining of lungs or abdominal cavities 
united insurance co and cigna reinsurance co the two other 
insurance companies involved in the case did not have an immediate 
comment to the decision owensillinois spokesman jeff hoff also 
declined comment 
new jersey has been the focus of much of the court action over 
asbestos exposure partly because it was the home of the 
johnsmanville corp formerly of manville nj 
now known as manville corp of denver the asbestos maker filed 
for bankruptcy protection in 1982 after a number of injury and 
wrongful death claims 
the company eventually settled the claims by contributing 600 
million to several trust funds meant to compensate those made ill 
by manville products 
