<TEXT>
the stateowned shipyard where workers 
founded the solidarity labor movement will be transferred to 
private ownership by selling shares to employees and the public 
its manager announced tuesday 
the fate of the shipyard in the northern port of gdansk had been 
uncertain since october 1988 when polands thencommunist 
government announced plans to close it solidarity leader lech 
walesa viewed the step as a political move but authorities said 
the shipyard was unprofitable and must be closed as part of 
economic reforms 
poland should finally understand that we were fighting for 
everybody but we got nothing out of it walesa told workers 
tuesday at a gdansk shipyard rally where the ownership transfer was 
announced the time of struggle is over now we are fighting 
for ourselves 
the manager of the shipyard hans szyt read a telegram from 
industry minister tadeusz syryjczyk announcing the decision during 
the rally by 2000 workers protesting the slow pace of government 
decisions on the shipyards fate 
the shares will be sold to the public for 105 each with the 
founding capital to total about 114 million said andrzej 
popczyk director of the industry ministrys legal department 
shipyard workers will be able to purchase 20 percent of the 
shares at half the offering price before the end of 1990 and at 
half the market price after that popczyk said 
the solidarityled government and parliament are working out 
complex reforms allowing the sale of state enterprises as part of a 
radical switch from a centrally planned socialist economy to a 
marketdriven system 
the state industries although largely unprofitable and 
outmoded make up much of polands national wealth and there has 
been widespread concern about how and at what price they will be 
sold to private investors 
few other details of the plan for the gdansk shipyard were 
offered immediately including the number of shares to be issued 
and the timetable for the sale 
when the communists were ousted and the solidarityled 
government took over last fall discussions began on how to save 
the highly symbolic shipyard 
one muchpublicized offer from the polishborn american heiress 
barbara piaseckajohnson seemed to fall through when terms could 
not be reached apparently because the workers were unwilling to 
accept the pay and nostrike agreements she required she has 
offered further negotiations 
the solidarity movement was born at the shipyard when walesa an 
electrician fired for union work scaled a fence to lead a strike 
in 1980 as the movement swept poland communist authorities were 
forced to recognize solidarity as the first legal independent trade 
union in the soviet bloc 
on dec 13 1981 martial law was imposed to repress 
solidaritys surging power but beset by a staggering economy and 
dispirited populace the communist regime was forced to turn to 
solidarity for help and relegalized the group in late 1988 
within a year the communists were trounced in largely 
democratic elections and the first noncommunist government in the 
east bloc was installed with a solidarity veteran as prime minister 
